<code>@reboot</code> configures a job to run once when the daemon is started. Since cron is typically never restarted, this typically corresponds to the machine being booted. This behavior is enforced in some variations of cron, such as that provided in [[Debian]],[http://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=77563#30 Bugs.debian.org] so that simply restarting the daemon does not re-run <code>@reboot</code> jobs.

<code>@reboot</code> can be useful if there is a need to start up a server or daemon under a particular user, and the user does not have access to configure [[init]] to start the program.

